Lifehack: Find the best city for you!¶

Mission¶

We wish to empower students with the data to help them narrow down which US city will be most suitable to live in based on their individual requirements. Please note that this problem statement was arrived at through a survey of the students in our data-science class.¶

We are going to meet the needs of our class by analyzing and aggregating various datasets such as weather, housing, economics and job outlook, by US city. The dataset will be focused primarily on the top 50 cities in US by population.

url = "http://www.intellicast.com/Local/History.aspx?unit=C&location=USCA0638"
urlreq = requests.get(url)
urltext = urlreq.text
soup = BeautifulSoup(urltext,'lxml')
res=[]
table = soup.find('table',{'class':'Container'})
My_table = soup.find('table',{'class':'Container'})
for items in My_table.find_all("tr"):
    data = [' '.join(item.text.split()) for item in items.find_all(['th','td'])]
    #print(data)
    if data:
        res.append(data)
headers = res.pop(0)
df_la = pd.DataFrame(res, columns=headers)
df_la["Month"]=df_la['Date']
df_la.drop(columns='Date',inplace=True)
df_la.drop(columns='RecordLow',inplace=True)
df_la.drop(columns='RecordHigh',inplace=True)
df_la.drop(columns='AveragePrecipitation',inplace=True)
df_la.drop(columns='AverageSnow',inplace=True)
df_la=df_la.applymap(lambda x: str(x.replace('°','')))
df_la["AverageLow"]=pd.to_numeric(df_la["AverageLow"])
df_la["AverageHigh"]=pd.to_numeric(df_la["AverageHigh"])
xlabels = list(df_la["Month"])
x = np.arange(1, 14, 1)
theta = theta = 2 * np.pi * (x - 1) / 12
y1 = list(df_la['AverageHigh'])
y1.append(df_la['AverageHigh'][0])
y2 = list(df_la["AverageLow"])
y2.append(df_la['AverageLow'][0])
plt.figure(figsize=(10,10))
ax = plt.subplot(111, projection='polar')
ax.plot(theta,y1,'r-',theta,y2,'b-')
ax.set_xticks(theta)
ax.set_rticks([-10,0,10,20,30,40])
ax.set_theta_zero_location("N")
plt.setp(ax.get_xticklabels(), visible=False)
bottom = 50
rotations = np.rad2deg(theta);
for x, rotation, label in zip(theta, rotations, df_la["Month"]):
    lab = ax.text(x,44, label, 
             ha='center', va='center', rotation=rotation, rotation_mode="anchor",fontsize=16)

ax.text(0, -7, 'Freezing', fontsize=12)
ax.text(0, 3, 'Cold', fontsize=12)
ax.text(0, 13, 'Mild', fontsize=12)
ax.text(0, 23, 'Pleasant', fontsize=12)
ax.text(0, 33, 'Hot', fontsize=12)

plt.legend(["ave max","ave min"],loc="best")
plt.title("Los Angeles, CA",fontsize=24,y=0.55);

INSIGHTS - Weather Temperature Radials by City¶

  1. Weather radials are a great way of visualizing and comparing weather in locations.
  2. Los Angeles, CA is pleasant to mild year round.
  3. New York, NY has a relatively large change in temperature during the year from pleasant to freezing.
  4. Seattle, WA is mostly mild, or cold year round.
  5. Austin, TX is hot to cold (surprisingly) year round.
  6. Buffalo, NY has a relatively large change in temperature during the year from pleasant to freezing.

NOTE: These are just a selection of cities. Future versions will include interface to select and compare cities.
